{
  "id": "019d2419-2c60-7d82-9919-661a6fe684a5",
  "content": "# Hook System Deep Dive — Research Findings (2026-03-25)\n\n## Orphan Cleanup: No Technical Reason for Bash\n- Every operation (pgrep, kill, ps, /proc/meminfo, /proc/version) has Rust equivalents via sysinfo, procfs, nix crates\n- Bash spawns ~16 subprocesses per run. Rust reads /proc once.\n- Script was bash because it was a quick WSL workaround, not by design\n- Should move to Rust with everything else\n\n## Telemetry Cold Start: Not Actually a Problem\n- corvia CLI cold start: 14ms (cold), 9ms (warm). Config load adds ~6ms.\n- bash+jq: 4-5ms per hook. Delta is only 5-15ms.\n- Over 100 hooks: 0.5-1.5 seconds total overhead — negligible\n- HOWEVER: the corvia server is already running (guaranteed by post-start.sh). Hooks could POST to server instead of spawning CLI.\n- Server endpoint approach: ~3-5ms per hook (faster than both bash and CLI)\n- Recommendation: Use server endpoint as primary, CLI as fallback. No daemon needed.\n\n## Server Dependency: JSONL IS Already a WAL\n- Current system already implements write-ahead log pattern: hooks write JSONL first, adapter replays later\n- Missing piece: retry logic in SessionEnd (currently try once, fail silently)\n- Industry patterns (OTEL Collector, Datadog Agent, Fluent Bit) all use WAL + bounded retry\n- For our scale (10-50 events/session, ~500 bytes each): strengthen the WAL, don't build a queue system\n- Right answer: JSONL-first recording + server endpoint for real-time + bounded retry on session end\n\n## Revised Architecture Decision\nInstead of `corvia hooks run` CLI subcommand, use dual-path:\n1. Real-time: POST to server `/v1/hooks/event` (3-5ms, server already warm)\n2. Durability: Always write JSONL first (WAL pattern, survives server downtime)\n3. Replay: SessionEnd triggers ingest with bounded retry (3 attempts, 2s backoff)\n4. All recording logic in Rust (server handler + CLI fallback), not bash",
  "source_version": "mcp",
